Comment: ```I’m not going to comment on URichmond, which I think is a great college.  I’m just going to comment on Haverford because I know much more about it than Richmond. Yes classes are shared in the consortium, and yes, most social events are open to both Haverford and BMC students, but honestly most of the BMC students are not spending tons of time at Haverford.  They chose BMC for a reason. Second, yes you can take Penn classes, and many students do.  It’s not hard to get to Penn from Haverford.  But I don’t think going to Haverford just so you can take a few classes at Penn is a good reason to choose the college.  Students at Haverford want to be at Haverford, not Penn.  The culture is very different from the one at Penn, so perhaps if you love the Wharton vibe Haverford isn’t a match. Haverford is filled with students who lean to the quirky/intellectual side.  It’s does not have the pre-professional vibe that Penn does.  It’s not very sporty, despite the fact that many students are on athletic teams.  It’s just another thing they might do on the side, not close to the most important thing they do. I think you are looking at 2 great colleges and you need to take some time to think about them.  Visit if you can.  And then just go with whichever one fits you best. Good luck deciding.  ```

params.context_instruct:
You will be given two colleges A and B, and a comment. Your job is to identify the preference between the two given colleges in the comment. 
The names of the two colleges and the comment are delimited with triple backticks.

I will ask you the following questions one by one.
1. Is there a preference between the two colleges in the comment?
2. If there is a preference, what is the preference between the two colleges?

Here are the shared rules for both questions:
You MUST NOT use the colleges' real names.
You MUST refer to the colleges as A or B. 
You MUST NOT respond with any other response. 
You MUST NOT make up a preference when there is no preference in the comment.
